1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:04,400
If you recall how we handle training data for transformers,

2

00:00:04,400  -->  00:00:11,520
we convert a single part of the training dataset into multiple training examples.

3

00:00:11,520  -->  00:00:16,080
One issue is that since a model sees the whole input,

4

00:00:16,080  -->  00:00:19,515
it can sheet when predicting the next word.

5

00:00:19,515  -->  00:00:24,980
To fix this problem, we need to change the attention scores we are calculating to

6

00:00:24,980  -->  00:00:31,235
ensure that our model can't look at the next token when it tries to predict it.

7

00:00:31,235  -->  00:00:35,290
To make sure that our model can sheet during training,

8

00:00:35,290  -->  00:00:42,380
we need to update the attention matrix and set all the highlighted values to 0.

9

00:00:42,380  -->  00:00:46,730
How would we do this? A simple way is to assign

10

00:00:46,730  -->  00:00:51,830
all values below this diagonal to the negative infinity.

11

00:00:52,030  -->  00:00:56,170
If you recall the properties of the softmax function,

12

00:00:56,170  -->  00:01:00,435
it converts small values into values close to 0.

13

00:01:00,435  -->  00:01:05,780
In this case, it will convert negative infinity values to 0s.

14

00:01:06,520  -->  00:01:11,960
Going back to our diagram of operations in the multi-head attention,

15

00:01:11,960  -->  00:01:17,380
we will add the masking step after the matrix multiplication,

16

00:01:17,380  -->  00:01:21,260
and we will apply softmax afterwards.

17

00:01:21,260  -->  00:01:27,980
This approach when we are using a triangular mask is called masked multi-head attention,

18

00:01:27,980  -->  00:01:34,320
and it is used in many transformer models, including GPT models.
